{{BLP sources|date=June 2018}} {{Infobox comedian | name = Dat Phan | image = DatPhan-wikipedia.jpg | imagesize = | caption = Dat Phan in 2010 at The Punchline in Sacramento, CA | pseudonym = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1975|1|25}} | birth_place = [[Saigon]], [[South Vietnam]] | residence = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S. | medium = [[Stand-up comedy|Stand-up]], television, film | nationality = [[Vietnamese Americans|Vietnamese American]] | active = 2003â€“present | genre = [[Observational comedy]] | subject = [[Everyday life]], [[self-deprecation]], [[racial stereotypes]]<ref name="NCTimes" /> | spouse = | notable_work = | signature = | website = {{url|http://datphan.com}} | emmyawards = }} '''Dat Phan''' (born January 25, 1975) is a [[Vietnamese American]] [[stand-up comedian]]. He first rose to fame in 2003 after defeating runner-up [[Ralphie May]] to win Season 1 of [[Last Comic Standing]].
==Early life== Phan was born in Saigon. When he was a child, he, his mother, and nine of his siblings [[emigrated]] from [[South Vietnam]] to the [[United States]]. They suffered financial hardships throughout his childhood. He grew up in the [[City Heights, San Diego, California|City Heights]] neighborhood of [[San Diego, California]], then spent his teenage years in [[Santee, California]], a [[suburb]] of San Diego. Phan was voted most successful of his class at his [[West Hills High School]] ten-year reunion, and was voted into [[Grossmont College]]'s [[Grossmont College#Walk of Fame|Walk of Fame]].<ref name="NCTimes">{{cite web|url=http://www.nctimes.com/entertainment/art-and-theater/theater/article_08631056-e5c2-51a0-b2a9-8d810dd34a5d.html|title=Locally raised comedian Phan grateful to be working|last=Curran|first=James|date=2 January 2008|publisher=North County Times|accessdate=20 February 2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100311182159/http://www.nctimes.com/entertainment/art-and-theater/theater/article_08631056-e5c2-51a0-b2a9-8d810dd34a5d.html|archivedate=11 March 2010|df=}}</ref>
==Career== In [[2003 in television|2003]], he entered the first season of [[NBC]]'s stand-up comedy competition [[reality show]], ''[[Last Comic Standing]]''.<ref name="NCTimes" /><ref name="AsianWeek">{{cite web|url=http://www.asianweek.com/2008/09/16/dat-phan-joins-jade-ribbon-campaign/|title=Dat Phan Joins Jade Ribbon Campaign|last=Pang|first=Angela|date=16 September 2008|publisher=AsianWeek|accessdate=20 February 2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100311182630/http://www.asianweek.com/2008/09/16/dat-phan-joins-jade-ribbon-campaign/|archivedate=11 March 2010|df=}}</ref> He was picked on by the other contestants due to his relative youth in the comedy world.<ref name="NCTimes" /> Nonetheless, Phan was the surprise winner of ''Last Comic Standing'',<ref name="AsianWeek" /> and subsequently has made cameo appearances in Hollywood films such as ''[[Cellular (film)|Cellular]]''<ref name="AsianWeek" /> and ''[[Love Is the Drug (film)|Love Is the Drug]]''. He currently resides in [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]], [[California]].
Dat Phan Productions released the DVD ''[[Dat Phan: Live]]'' and the CD ''[[You Touch, You Buy]]'', in stores January 2010, and began pre-production on a movie titled ''Yellow Fever''.<ref name="AsianWeek" /> He has endorsed the Jade Ribbon Campaign established to fight against hepatitis B and liver cancer.<ref name="AsianWeek" />
In 2011, Phan was featured in the [[DirecTV]] campaign, "The Whale".
